<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-170-231 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 690 869</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 29 1991 v25 n17 p60(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virtual servers lighten load; software lets key data stay onworkstations, off host. (International Business Software Inc.'sDataclub computer network software for the Apple Macintosh)(product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nash, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Dataclub, computer network software made by International BusinessSoftware Inc, runs on Apple Macintosh networks.andP;  It is priced at$395 for a three-user license, $795 for 10 users, and $3,250 for50 users.andP;  Dataclub compiles information about the files andvolumes on an Apple network, giving each node the name and statusof a file under a single icon, as if all of the files were locatedon a single file server even if they are actually residing onindividual workstations.andP;  This 'virtual server' approach helpsnetwork users avoid slowing down a network's performance bytrading large or frequently-used files over the network duringpeak usage times.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   DataClub (Computer network software) (Product introduction)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Computer programs).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionNetwork SoftwareFile Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>